## What I changed

**Added the Tombstone beat (the review's biggest catch).** The reviewer was right that its absence read like the draft was dodging its best counter-example. I folded it into the Snake Plissken section as the *exception that proves the rule*: I first established the director-merge as a pattern (Carpenter, then Tarantino in one line), then hit Tombstone — where Russell, by his own True West account, ran the shoot and fed credited director George Cosmatos a nightly shot list, then refused the credit: *"I don't want to put my name on it. I don't want to be the guy."* That quote is the exact "keep my name off it" move, so it sharpens the thesis instead of breaking it. I flagged the castmate dispute (Kilmer, Biehn) honestly rather than overclaiming, and tied it back to the wine label "run in reverse."

**Added the family gap.** The portrait was built on "raised kids who weren't his by blood" but never mentioned his own. Added the brief first marriage to Season Hubley and biological son Boston — and turned Boston's well-documented privacy into an on-thesis beat (the one kid who "inherited the family instinct for keeping his name off the label").

**Trimmed the repetition.** Cut the reused "cage door" metaphor from the ending (it now lives only in the Goldie section, where it's Hawn's own); removed the third/fourth wine restatement in the close; dropped the "never worked" echo from the waste-talent opener; and recast two "not X / a Y" fragments to soften the contrast-engine template.

